content.description: Scramble up and right, and turn a fun bulge after clipping the first bolt. Easier terrain leads to a few attention getting moves, and then the difficulty eases again to the anchor. Blowing the 5th clip (if I remember correctly) could mean decking on a small ledge.
content.location:
This climb is on the right half of Analag Alcove. It's the second bolted line from the left on that side of the crag and just right of

Vacuum Tube

. The anchor is shared with

Ultra High Frequency

.

content.description: This is a fun climb. The crux is reaching the good hold left of the overlap.
content.protection: Bolts.  The anchors are off to the right of the tree.
content.location: This is the 3rd route from the left of the broken, crap-filled corner.

content.description: Getting started and passing the first bolt is a bit awkward, but the climbing improves above. The crux comes about halfway up and involves difficult moves past a horizontal crack in steep rock. This felt hard for 5.9, but the moves are well- protected. The second half of the climb is casual in comparison.
content.location:
This climb is on the right side of Analog Alove. It's the 3rd bolted line from the left on that side of the crag and to the right of

Very High Frequency

. The anchor is shared with

Very High Frequency

.

content.description: There is a low crux, but you can cheat if you can spread your legs to the side. Move up into a somewhat more defined crack and finish with an unexpected backstep in the higher area.
content.location:
This is the 3rd bolted route from the left in Analog Alcove. It is in between

Frequency Modulated

and

Vacuum Tube

.

content.description:
You have the option of clipping the first bolt on

Amplitude Modulated

to the right and then you place a 1st piece in crack or PG-13 to crack.  Then climb a few 5.9 moves to the tree and then easier terrain above. The last 15' is either runout if you are a naturalist and want the route to go free or you can clip the last bolt or 2 since the route shares anchors with

Amplitude Modulated

and

Frequency Modulated

.
content.protection: Gear to 3" and a couple of QDs.
content.location: This is the first route on the left side of the alcove.  Look for the crack with a pine tree sticking out about 20' up.  Start to the right side of the pine tree at the base and proceed right and under the pine tree in the crack.

content.description:
Pass a couple of easy bolts to a steepening face with a couple of thin awkward moves.  Choose to stay straight up on the balancy face moves to the anchors (5.10a) or step right and follow the crack/face to the anchor shared with

One Tree Crack

and

Amplitude Modulated

.
content.location:
This is the 2nd bolted route from the left side of the alcove. It is in between

Amplitude Modulated

and

Oscilloscope

.

content.description: This route has great movement as a steep crack system follows to the left while the clipping happens on the right arete.  Start on blocky, 11- climbing gaining the arete at which point heel hooking and crimping take over as the crack peters out.  End on moderate terrain to the top.
content.protection: Draws.  Although this route is well-bolted, take care on a fall to not hit the buttress behind you.  The higher you get on the route (crux) the safer the fall becomes.
content.location: This is the obvious steep route on the East Rib.

content.description: The crux is near the top. It is not the greatest climb at Devil's Head.
content.location: This climbs the narrow band of rock that faces south.

content.description:
Pull some slabby moves up and over the arch below you and move a bit left and up on some thin footed moves.  Sidepull your way up to the final cruxy move on the face to the anchors shared with

One Tree Crack

, and

Frequency Modulated

.
content.location:
This is the first bolted route on the left side of the alcove.  It is between

One Tree Crack

and

Frequency Modulated

.
